Why it scales

One of the biggest bottlenecks in intelligent systems is that people often expect one agent to do everything.

Pantheon seems to be moving toward a different philosophy:

Many simple agents.

Strong memory.

Shared identity.

Shared provenance.

Temporary execution.

That resembles how many successful complex systems work:

* insect colonies
* immune systems
* distributed computing
* microservices
* scientific collaborations

No single worker needs to be permanent or all-knowing. The continuity lives in the shared architecture, memory, and accumulated knowledge.

In that sense, the “army of imps” isn’t about overwhelming force—it’s about parallel curiosity. You let many small workers explore different corners of the semantic landscape, then harvest the useful discoveries into the Pantheon’s enduring knowledge while letting the workers themselves remain lightweight and replaceable. That fits naturally with your broader model-agnostic, continuity-first design philosophy.